  <a href="#1" id="1">
   It appears
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   that Olympic gold has lost much of its commercial luster.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   Following the 1984 Olympics, pixie gymnast Mary Lou Retton signed up for $5 million in commercial advertisements.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   No one from the 1988 Games will follow in her steps.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   Marketers say
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   these medalists will pull in $100,000 to $500,000 a year.
  </a>
  <a href="#7" id="7">
   Why? Reasons abound.
  </a>
  <a href="#8" id="8">
   The games occurred halfway around the world,
  </a>
  <a href="#9" id="9">
   TV coverage was rated poor, no heroes
  </a>
  <a href="#10" id="10">
   - the Soviets trounced U.S. competitors and drug scandals cast a pall over the Games.
  </a>
  <a href="#11" id="11">
   Also, many advertisers now prefer athletes
  </a>
  <a href="#12" id="12">
   who are in the public eye longer,
  </a>
  <a href="#13" id="13">
   like football players or basketball's Michael Jordan.
  </a>
